vergessenen Humanisten, der an die friedensstiftende Kraft der Kultur glaubte.  aDuring the 1930s the Vienna-born writer Emil Alphons Rheinhardt (1889–1945) lived in the town of Le Lavandou in the South France, where he made his house a hospitable meeting place for German-speaking literary exiles. In 1943, during the German occupation of France, Rheinhardt was arrested and then in 1944 deported to Dachau concentration camp, where he died shortly before the liberation. A few years ago the historian Dominique Lassaigne discovered his prison diary, which had been believed lost. Rheinhardt’s notes from the Gestapo prisons bear witness to a long-forgotten humanist who believed in the peacemaking power of culture.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAuthors, Austriany20th centuryvBiography. 0aHolocaust survivorsvDiaries. 0aPrisoners' writings, German. 0aWar victimsvDiaries. 4aEdition. 4aExil Frankreich. 4aLiteratur der Konzentrationslager. 4aRheinhardt, Emil Alphons. 4aTagebuch. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aDiary.  aEdition.  aExile France.  aLiterature from the Concentration Camps.  aRheinhardt, Emil Alphons.1 aGeorget, Jean-Louis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLassaigne, Dominique, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwarz, Uta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwarz, Uta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERA